# shine-links ✦

A shine sweep animation for links. One script tag, nothing else.

---

## How it works

When you load `shine.js` it:
1. Injects the `.shine` CSS into your page automatically
2. Finds every `<a>` tag and adds the `shine` class to it
3. The animation runs — no setup needed

---

## Usage

```html
<body>

  <a href="/docs">Documentation</a>
  <a href="/blog">Blog</a>

  <!-- load before </body>, not in <head> -->
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/shine-links@latest/shine.js"></script>

</body>
```

That's all. No JS to call, no class to add manually.

---

## Common mistakes

**❌ Don't load it in `<head>`**
```html
<!-- wrong — element doesn't exist yet when script runs -->
<head>
  <script src="shine.js"></script>
</head>
```

```html
<!-- correct — always before </body> -->
<body>
  ...
  <script src="shine.js"></script>
</body>
```

**❌ Don't call `new ShineLinks()` or any function**
```js
// wrong — this API doesn't exist
new ShineLinks('.shine');
ShineLinks.init();
```
The script runs automatically. You don't call anything.

**❌ Don't override `.shine` CSS with `position: static` or remove `overflow: hidden`**
```css
/* wrong — breaks the clipping, causes a visible box */
.shine {
  position: static;
  overflow: visible;
}
```
If you need to style the link, target it before the shine class:
```css
/* correct */
a {
  color: white;
  font-size: 2rem;
  text-decoration: none;
}
```

---

## Apply to specific elements only

By default it applies to all `<a>` tags. To apply manually to a single element:

```html
<h1 class="shine">Hello</h1>
```

Or via JS:
```js
document.querySelector(".my-link").classList.add("shine");
```

---

## Install options

**CDN — recommended:**
```html
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/shine-links@latest/shine.js"></script>
```

**npm:**
```bash
npm install shine-links
```
```js
import "shine-links";
```

**Direct download:**
Grab `shine.js` from [github.com/havishhexe/shiny](https://github.com/havishhexe/shiny) and host it yourself.

---

## Dark vs light backgrounds

The default streak is white at `0.55` opacity which works on both dark and light backgrounds. If you want to tweak it, copy `shine.js` locally and adjust this line:

```js
background: linear-gradient(105deg, transparent 30%, rgba(255,255,255,0.55) 50%, transparent 70%);
```

Increase opacity for dark backgrounds, decrease for light.

